Cinderella is a classic folk tale about a beautiful girl who, despite being mistreated by her wicked stepfamily, finds happiness with a prince thanks to a magical intervention. ​ Cinderella's Life and Family Cinderella lived with a wicked stepmother and two stepsisters who treated her very poorly. She was forced to perform all the household chores, including sewing gowns and styling hair for her family members. When an invitation arrived for a grand ball at the king’s palace, her stepmother refused to let her attend. ​ The Fairy Godmother's Magic As Cinderella wept, a fairy godmother appeared and used a magic wand to transform her circumstances. The magic created a golden coach from a pumpkin and turned six mice into four shiny black horses and two coachmen. Cinderella’s old rags were replaced with a beautiful gown and a pair of delicate glass slippers. ​ The Grand Palace Ball The fairy godmother warned Cinderella that the magic would expire exactly at midnight. Upon arriving at the palace, Cinderella's beauty stunned everyone, including her stepfamily, who did not recognize her. The prince immediately fell in love and danced with her throughout the entire evening. ​ A Hasty Midnight Exit Distracted by her happiness, Cinderella nearly forgot the midnight deadline and had to rush out of the palace. In her hurry, she lost one of her glass slippers on the stairs but did not stop to retrieve it. At the final stroke of twelve, her coach, horses, and fine clothes returned to their original forms. ​ Search for the Slipper The prince, determined to marry the woman who fit the glass slipper, searched every house in the kingdom. Although the stepmother tried to prevent Cinderella from participating, the prince insisted she try on the shoe. The slipper fit perfectly, leading the prince to recognize her, and they lived happily ever after. ​